    "body": "### Problem\n\nCompleting file names (i_CTRL-X_CTRL-F) doesn't work correctly on Windows. It seems to assume that all files are on the same drive as the current working directory. That means that you need to `:cd` to the other drive to get completion to work there.\n\nI've reproduced on both 0.11.1 and 0.11.4 (latest stable).\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```\npushd c:\nmkdir c:\\only_on_c\nmkdir e:\\only_on_e\nnvim --clean\nie:\\only<C-x><C-f>\n:cd e:\\\nie:\\only<C-x><C-f>\nic:\\only<C-x><C-f>\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nOffers completion for non-existent `e:\\only_on_c` instead of the correct `only_on_e`. Once the cwd is on the e: drive, then it offers the correct completion for e: paths (but now they're incorrect for c: paths).\n\nOn vim, it works correctly both with and without using `:cd e:\\`.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.11.4\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, vim 9.0.1576\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWin 11\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nWin Terminal\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nnone\n\n### Installation\n\nscoop",
